 of his writings on rhetoric. That Melanchthon played a central role in the transformation of the ancient discipline has been well established by historians. His writings on rhetoric have proven significant sources for several academic fields, including church history, Scriptural interpretation, the history of science, and the reception of classical literature. Remarkably, two of the three principal writings have not been published in their entirety since the sixteenth century. This volume collects critical editions of the three principal writings to provide a more complete record of Melanchthon's teaching of rhetoric. It includes critical editions of De Rhetorica (1519), Institutiones Rhetoricae (1521), and Elementa Rhetorices (1531). In addition to the three principal writings, this volume collects a new edition, based on a 1911 edition by Hanns Zwicker, of Dispositiones Rhetoricae (c. 1553), a manuscript compilation of 161 model themes. Scholars will find in this volume the major sources for Melanchthon's theory and practice of rhetorical instruction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Latin.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jan 2018) 4aDialectic. 4aDialektik. 4aReformation. 4aRenaissance. 4aRhetoric. 4aRhetorik.1 aStrohm, Stefan, eeditor.1 aWeaver, William P., eeditor.1 aWels, Volkhard, eeditor.0 cbundlez97831105612030 cprintz978311055955240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110561197423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110561197.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK